The ordering of the `Flowable.create` parameters makes it impossible to use trailing closures in Kotlin, causing calls that look like this:

```kotlin
Flowable.create({ emitter ->
  // etc...
}, LATEST)
```

If the declaration were `Flowable.create(BackpressureStrategy, FlowableOnSubscribe<T>)` it would be possible to do this instead:

```kotlin
Flowable.create(LATEST) { emitter ->
  // etc...
}
```

Ordinarily, I'd solve this by making an extension function on the class, but Kotlin can't add static methods to java classes as they lack a `companion object`.

