We've faced an issue using `doOnSubscribe` (yeah, yeah, side-effects, managed to refactor this though).

Test that shows the problem (RxJava 1.x):

``` java
@Test
public void define_whenSubscribed_please() {
    final PublishSubject<String> publishSubject = PublishSubject.create();
    final TestSubscriber<String> subscriber = new TestSubscriber<String>();

    publishSubject
            .doOnSubscribe(new Action0() {
                @Override
                public void call() {
                    publishSubject.onNext("value1");
                    // If you'll do it on separate thread with delay, subscriber will see value.
                }
            })
            .subscribe(subscriber);

    subscriber.assertValue("value1");
}
```

This test fails with `AssertionError: Number of items does not match. Provided: 1  Actual: 0.`.

If action have some threading (especially with io) involved this may result in "sometimes/mostOfTheTime works, rarely doesn't" because there'll be a race between side-effect execution and actual subscription of the subscriber.

Javadoc is not very clear about the time _when_ action will be invoked: 

``` java
the action that gets called when an observer subscribes to the source {@code Observable}
```

I suggest to deprecate this operator in 1.x and add `doBeforeSubscribe` as a replacement and do the same for 2.x without deprecation.

