I'm sorry but no. `Subscription` is a deliberately minimal interface with one objective: unsubscribe a potential chain of resources. Since we are **Java 6, no default methods are allowed** (besides, it would lead to cyclic dependency between the two), plus **we have to maintain binary compatibility** and changing `Subscription` into an abstract class would break it.

Why not have a static method somewhere which you import statically what does the boilerplate for you:

``` java
public static <T> void subscribeForMe(
        Observable<T> source, Subscriber<? super T> subscriber, 
        CompositeSubscription container) {
    container.add(source.subscribe(subscriber));
}

CompositeSubscription compositeSubscription = new CompositeSubscription();

subscribeForMe(Observable.just("test"), new Subscriber<String>() {
            @Override public void onCompleted() { }

            @Override public void onError(Throwable e) { }

            @Override public void onNext(String s) {  }
        }, 
    compositeSubscription);
```

