Also, on a general note, the fact that error propagation always unsubscribes and the only way to gracefully handle it is to resubscribe seems to limit the fluency of RxJava in a lot of use cases. The solutions suggested here show that there is no fluent way of propagating errors without disrupting the normal flow of events. I think a more straightforward solution will be:

``` java
    private static class AccumulatedState {
        private AccumulatedState() {
            times = "";
        }

        String times;
        Throwable throwable;
    }

    public static void scanWithErrorContext() {
        data()
                .scan(new AccumulatedState(), (accumulatedState, time) -> {
                    if (time.endsWith("5"))
                        accumulatedState.throwable = new Exception("wow");
                    else {
                        accumulatedState.throwable = null;
                        accumulatedState.times = accumulatedState.times + "," + time;
                    }
                    return accumulatedState;
                })
                .take(15)
                .toBlocking()
                .forEach(accumulatedState -> {
                    if (accumulatedState.throwable != null) {
                        System.out.println("Error: " + accumulatedState.throwable);
                    } else {
                        System.out.println(accumulatedState.times);
                    }
                });
    }
```

But it seems so generic that it should be part of the framework (something like `subscriber.onSilentError`).
Thanks, Amitai.

